In 🌐 Step 6: Controller  where is the UserRepository class to  save ?


Ahh good catch 👏 — this confusion is very normal when building layers for the first time.

Let’s clear it properly so you never get confused again.

🧠 Your Question

“In Controller → where is UserRepository used?”

👉 Short answer:

Controller ❌ does NOT use Repository directly
Controller ✅ uses Service
Service ✅ uses Repository
🏗️ Correct Flow (VERY IMPORTANT)
Controller → Service → Repository → Database
🔍 Let’s map YOUR classes
1️⃣ Controller
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {

    @Autowired
    private UserService userService;   // ✅ NOT repository

    @PostMapping
    public User createUser(@RequestBody User user) {
        return userService.saveUser(user);
    }
}

👉 Controller talks only to:

UserService ✅
2️⃣ Service (THIS is where Repository comes)
@Service
public class UserService {

    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;  // ✅ HERE

    public User saveUser(User user) {
        return userRepository.save(user);   // DB operation
    }
}

👉 Service talks to:

UserRepository ✅
3️⃣ Repository
public interface UserRepository extends JpaRepository<User, Long> {
}

👉 This directly talks to:

Database
🎯 Why this design?
❌ If Controller uses Repository directly:
Tight coupling ❌
Hard to maintain ❌
No business logic layer ❌
✅ With Service layer:
Clean architecture ✅
Easy to scale ✅
Add logic later (validation, rules) ✅
💡 Real-world analogy

Think like this:

Controller = Receptionist 🧑‍💼
Service = Manager 👨‍💼
Repository = Worker 👷
DB = Storage 🏬

👉 Receptionist doesn’t go to storage directly 😄

